tmodern criticism which claim to expose the simplistic methodology of `traditional' criticism and to offer a more sophisticated view of the relation between literature and history; however, this new approach, although making scholars more alert to the political significance of literary texts, has been widely criticised on both methodological and theoretical grounds. The revisionist essays collected in this volume make a major contribution to the modern debate on historical method, approaching Renaissance culture from different gender perspectives and a variety of political standpoints, but all sharing an interest in the interdisciplinary study of the past.ROBIN HEADLAM WELLS is Professor of English, University of Surrey Roehampton; GLENN BURGESS is Professor of History, University of Hull; ROWLAND WYMER is Senior Lecturer in English at the University of Hull. Contributors: GLENN BURGESS, STANLEY STEWART, BLAIR WORDEN, ANDREW GURR, KATHARINE EISAMAN MAUS, ROWLAND WYMER, GRAHAM PARRY, MALCOLM SMUTS, STEVEN ZWICKER, HEATHER DUBROW,ROBIN HEADLAM WELLS.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismyEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aHistoricism in literature. 0aLiterature and historyxHistoryy16th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aLiterature and historyxHistoryy17th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aPolitics and literaturexHistoryy16th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aPolitics and literaturexHistoryy17th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aRenaissancezEngland. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aModern History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aEnglish Renaissance culture.  aRenaissance literary scholarship.  agender perspectives.  ahistorical method.  apolitical standpoints.1 aBurgess, Glenn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb